  "diagnostic_reasoning": "Checking the ignition timing is a direct way to assess the condition of the timing chain and the distributor's function. A consistently retarded timing mark (relative to FSM specifications for the M117 USA engine: 5° ATDC at 800 rpm and 18-22° BTDC at 3000 rpm) strongly indicates timing chain stretch. A stretched chain would explain both the rattling noise on startup (slack in the chain) and the gradual power loss (retarded valve and ignition timing). If the timing is within specification, the power loss is not due to retarded ignition timing, and we would need to investigate other systems. An unstable or wandering timing mark could point to severe chain wear or a fault within the distributor's mechanical advance mechanisms.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "Observe the ignition timing mark with a stroboscope at both idle (800 rpm) and 3000 rpm, as per FSM procedure 07.5.0-510. Compare your readings to the M117 USA specifications: 5° ATDC at 800 rpm and 18-22° BTDC at 3000 rpm (07.5.1-515). Report what you physically observe regarding the stability and position of the timing mark.",
